<div class="comment-text">
<p>In your part of the article, you seem to dismiss the idea that white privilege and systemic racism can account for the difference in outcomes between racial groups.  Do you think that biological differences are *completely* responsible for the disparity in IQ between (for example) whites and blacks, or could historical and contemporary patterns of discrimination play some role?  In other words, are you convinced that people of African descent are (on average) innately and irredeemably inferior to people of European descent, or could social policies help to reduce the achievement gap?</p>
